{
  "texts": [
    "But this claim -that the movements are, in principle, available absent the laces -goes somewhat beyond what he needs.",
    "It might be the case that having the laces in hand is causally necessary for performing just such a movement while still not being constitutive of the movement that according to his version of the A-D principle is identical with the agent's action.",
    "Recall that it is the constitutive claim that the action theoretic argument outlined in (§3.3) requires.",
    "So, one end of the causal profile of an action is already fixed: its most proximate psychological cause must be something that could play the role of a primary reason.",
    "Notice that this rationalising cause needn't represent the basic action as such (i.e., as a bare bodily movement, subject to the Strict Bodily Constraint)."
  ]
}